# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
##### The idea here is to see how many words can be added to a line with only one space between the words, and then adding the required padding to the sentences, if needed. And left justify the last line of the paragraph.

__Its is easy to understand that__ `n` __words on a line with require__`n-1`__space, at least. Now, if we have `k` words on a line and__ `maxWidth` __as__ `mw`__. Then the extra space available to us will be__ `mw` - `length of all words combine`, __say__ `extra space`.
Now This extra space has to be even distributed among the k words, i.e. in `k-1` spaces between the words.__

__One more thing to note here is that if only one word can be accomodated in the line, then we just have to fill the rest of the line with spaces,__ `extra space`__.__

##### Lets take an Example :
`Words: {"This","is","my","house"}`, `maxWidth` __= 34
Now in order to check how many words can be placed in one line, we can traverse the entire array of words, and we can keep adding the words to a line till the following condition is satisfied:__ 

`curr_length of words` + `number of words - 1` <= `maxWidth`

 `number of words - 1` : This is used because we will be putting atleast one space between the words on the same line.

__Once the we know the number of words, we can get the minimum spaces that has to be put between the words, For our example__
`Length of all words` = 13, `number of words` = 4;
__therefore, by the condition mentioned before, all the words can be placed in one line.__
`extra space` = `maxWidth` - `length of all words combined`
`extra space` = 35 - 13 = 22
__So 22 spaces are to filled in 3 blanks, between 4 words__
padding : Minimum spaces to be filled in between gaps to reach maxWidth
__`padding` = `extra space`/ `number of words - 1` = 22/3 = 7__
__We still have 1 space left, that needs to be adjusted, 
consider ut as `extra padding`, that is given by 
`extra space` % `number of words - 1`__
__This means 1 extra space will be added to first `x` pairs,__
`x` = `extra padding`

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
__We will be using a two pointer approach to add the words from the starting index to the ending index. To do this create two variables:
 `start`: To track the index of the first word of the current line 
`end` : To track the index of last word of the current line
`curr_len` : To store the current length of the sentence__


>## Traverse the array of words
> `wd` = `end - start + 1` __gives the number of words in the current line__
   `curr_len` = `length of the words in the line` + `wd`
__adding wd accounts for the minimum number of spaces between each pair of words(i.e. 1).__
>### If `curr_len`  + `size of the current word` <= `maxWidth`
>> __Add the size of current word to `curr_len`, and incresae the word count, by increasing `end` = `end + 1`__
> 
> ### Else
>> __It's time to fix the current line / sentence and move on to the next one__
>> __Start the `sentence` as the word at index `start`
Calculate the `extra_space` = `maxWidth` - `curr_len`
`padding` = `extra_space` / `max(1 , wd - 1)`
`extra` = `extra_space` % `max(1 , wd - 1)`__
>> ###### __Padding adding is the minimum space that will be added between each pair of words, even distribution__
>> ###### __Extra is the uneven distribution of space required to reach the `maxWidth` length__
>> __Traverse from index `start + 1` to `end`__
>>>__Add the padding to the `sentence`
Add the extra padding
Add the `curr_word`
IF there is only one word__
>>>> __Fill the rest of the line with space__
>>>
>>> __Add the `sentence` to the `ans` vector
Set :
`start` as `end + 1`, 
`curr_len` = `curr_word.size()`, 
`end` = `end + 1`__
>>
> #### __Once the Loop is exited, we are left with the last line, that is to be left-justified__
>__Start the `sentence` as the word at index `start`
Traverse from index `start + 1` to `end`__
>>__Add a space to the `sentence`
Add the `curr_word`__
>
>__Fill the rest of the line with spaces
Add the `sentence` to the `ans` vector
Return the answer vector `ans`__

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n*k*padding)$$ 
   n = number of words
   k = max number of words that can be added in a line
   padding = minimum space between a pair of words
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(1)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
