solutions.content:
# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Partition approach will work as we have to store as many consecutive words possible in a line, with a constraint that every word is separate by atleast one space with another word. 

So, for a line to be valid, the constraints come out to be -
`totalLengthOfTheWordsInTheLine + totalNumberOfWordsInTheCurrentLine - 1 <= maxWidth`
So for a line to contain 3 words,the sum  of lengths of all the three words and 2 spaces should be less than or equal to maxWidth.

As soon as the constraint is broken or the length of the line becomes greater than maxWidth, we start storing word in a new line.

---
```
For Example -
words = ["abc","ab","ab","a","fgabc"]
maxWidth = 7

Output - 
"abc-ab-"
"ab---a-"
"fgabc--"

where '-' represent a single space
```

The first line contains abc,ab only and not abc,ab,ab because the words need to be separated by atleast one space, so the length of line abc,ab,ab would be `(3 + 2 + 2) + (3-1) = 7 + 2 = 9`, that would excede the maxWidth criteria, so "ab" on index 2 goes to a new line.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
We initialize line1 with length of `word[0]`. Since it is the only word in the line and the last word should not be followed by a space, the total length of the line1 remains the same.
We iterate over the words array from `i = 1 to n-1`, storing words in a vector `temp`that belongs to same line, checking if the ith word can be added to the current line. We will be taking a separate variable,`prevLen` to store the totalLengthOfTheWords in the current line, and updating it while iterating. The least number of spaces the current line will be having for adding the current word is `lineSpaces = temp.size()`,i.e., `temp.size() - 1` for existing words, and `+ 1` for adding current word, so overall, `temp.size()` spaces.

The condition of being added to the current line being - 
`prevLen + lineSpaces + curWordLength <= maxWidth`.
So for creating a new line, condition becomes - 
`prevLen + lineSpaces + curWordLength > maxWidth`
After a line, `temp`, can no longer hold more words, we add it to the `lines` vector, and store the space the line can have in a `space` vector, as `maxWidth - prevLen`.

Note - After iteration, we have to add the last line in the `lines` vector as it won't be added in the iterating loop.

After storing all the lines and the corresponding number of spaces they can have. We will be iterating over all the lines and converting them into string with spaces, and store in the `ans` vector.

We have two justifications for a line-
1. <b>Left Only Justification</b> - For line containing one word, and the last line.
2. <b>Left and Right Justification</b> - For all the other lines not mentioned in 1.

So to append spaces, we have three states -
1. <b>When the line is the last line, or the line contains only one word -</b>
In this case, we will be adding only one space after every word, except the last word. The remaining spaces will be added after the last word, to make it left justified 

2. <b>The line which is not the last line, and contains more than one word-</b>
In this case, we will find out the least number of spaces that we can add between two consecutive words by `sp = space[i]/(numberOfWords-1)`, extra space being `spExtra = space[i]%(numberOfWords-1)`.
As to distribute `space[i]` between `numberOfWords` words, even space will be `sp`, and `extraSpace` that is used only `1` time after each word until it becomes `0`. <i>As per the question statement - <b>'Extra spaces between words should be distributed as evenly as possible. If the number of spaces on a line does not divide evenly between words, the empty slots on the left will be assigned more spaces than the slots on the right.'</b></i>
Since extra spaces will be less than the total positions where we can add space, i.e., `spExtra < sp`, therefore we will be adding only `1` extra space, if `spExtra` is not already exhausted.

# Complexity
- <b>Time complexity: $$O(n+n*maxWidth)$$</b>
-$$O(n)$$ for storing character in their respective line
-$$O(n.maxWidth)$$ for iterating over all lines to store answer.
In worst case, every line contains a single word, so `n` lines, and for each line we iterate over `maxWidth` characters, to append word characters and spaces. So total iteration becomse $$n*maxWidth$$

- <b>Space complexity: $$O(n + n*TotalWordLength+TotalWrdLength + maxWidth)$$</b>
Since, maximmum number of lines will be `n` in worst case, therefore space utiltized by 
-`space` vector for storing space will be $$O(n)$$.
-Maximum space utilized by `line` vector will be $$O(n*totalWordLength)$$. Since it stores words only.
-$$O(TotalWordLength)$$ for `temp` vector.
-String `curr` will also have space complexity of $$O(maxWidth)$$, as it will contain maxWidth characters.
So total space complexity will be $$O(n + n*TotalWordLength+TotalWrdLength + maxWidth)$$
