solutions.content:
First thing, text justification is very common in word processing tools like MSWord `(Ctrl + j)`.

**We need to think on below points:**

1. How do we know how many words would fit in each line?
2. Once we know the how many words would fit in current line, how do we divide the spaces? What if spaces are uneven? How do we handle such part?
3. How do we handle last line?

**Lets think . . .** 

We can add the length of the words as we go forward + we need to add 1 space at-least just after every word we encounter. We’ll stop as soon as we couldn’t fit any more word bounded by `maxWidth`.

**We can use two pointers to do that. Previous pointer will mark the starting of the word and next pointer will mark the ending of the word for the current line. We also need a sum that keeps track of how many characters it has seen yet.**

Let’s code the basic part

```cpp
int startWordIndex = 0;
int endWordIndex = 0;
int charsTillNow = 0;

while (endWordIndex < int(words.size())) {
    if (charsTillNow + int(words[endWordIndex].size()) <= maxWidth) {
        charsTillNow += int(words[endWordIndex].size());
        endWordIndex++;
    }
}
```

Above logic is wrong, we also need to add “space” while checking `<= maxWidth`. 

```cpp
int startWordIndex = 0;
int endWordIndex = 0;
int charsTillNow = 0;

while (endWordIndex < int(words.size())) {
    if (charsTillNow + 1 + int(words[endWordIndex].size()) <= maxWidth) {
        charsTillNow += int(words[endWordIndex].size());
        endWordIndex++;
    }
    // we come here means we cannot accomodate any more word for current line
}
```

Above logic is also wrong, we can’t add 1 for the first word of the current line. We need something that will make above code add 0 for the first time then 1 each time afterwards.

```cpp
int startWordIndex = 0;
int endWordIndex = 0;
int charsTillNow = 0;

bool startWord = true; // true for first word for each new line**
while (endWordIndex < int(words.size())) {
    int tempCharCount = charsTillNow + int(words[endWordIndex].size());
    if (!startWord) tempCharCount++; // For space after if not the first word
    if (tempCharCount <= maxWidth) {
        charsTillNow += tempCharCount;
        endWordIndex++;
        startWord = false;
        continue;
    }
    // we come here means we cannot accomodate any more word for current line
		// means after this next time while loop will be executed that would be for new line
    startWord = true;
}
```

Now, `charTillNow` will have all the valid chars count + 1 space b/w each word.

**How many words?**  `wordCount = endWordIndex - startWordIndex`

**How many spaces?** We must subtract the additional spaces we considered in `charsTillNow`. Those would be `wordCount-1`.

`spaceCount = maxWidth - (charsTillNow - (wordCount-1))`

**How much minimum space to allocate?**

`minSpaceForEachWord = spaceCount / (wordCount-1)` —> Division by 0 is likely

**What about any extra space left? Due to improper division of spaceCount and space locations**

`extraSpace = spaceCount - (spaceLocations * minSpaceForEachWord)`

We’ll add these additional space from left to right as we go forward with each word of the current line. Note that `extraSpace` will be less than `minSpaceForEachWord` as its the remainder. so if we add 1 by 1 if its more than 0, we’ll run out before the last word. [as per problem constraint]

**Let’s add these words bounded by [startWordIndex : endWordIndex)**

```cpp
string currentLine;

while(startWordIndex < endWordIndex) {
    currentLine.append(words[startWordIndex]);
    // Now add space but do not add space for last word
    if (startWordIndex != endWordIndex - 1)
        currentLine.append(string(minSpaceForEachWord + int(extraSpace > 0), ' '));
    startWordIndex++;
		extraSpace--; // even goes to negative, we really don't care
}
```

Note: if `extraSpace > 0` → `int(extraspace>0)` will return 1 for `true`.

Full code till now:
```
vector<string> fullJustify(vector<string>& words, int maxWidth) {
        vector<string> ans;
        int startWordIndex = 0;
        int endWordIndex = 0;
        int charsTillNow = 0;
        int wordCount, spaceLocations, spaceCount, minSpaceForEachWord, extraSpace;
        string currentLine;

        bool startWord = true;
        while (endWordIndex < int(words.size())) {
            int tempCharCount = int(words[endWordIndex].size());
            if (!startWord) tempCharCount++; // For space
            if (tempCharCount + charsTillNow <= maxWidth) {
                charsTillNow += tempCharCount;
                endWordIndex++;
                startWord = false;
                continue;
            }

            startWord = true;
            wordCount = endWordIndex - startWordIndex;
            spaceLocations = wordCount - 1; // we put space b/w each word so it will always be wordCount-1
            spaceCount = maxWidth - (charsTillNow - spaceLocations);

			// put the default value as full space count as we also need to handle if we found just one word
            // for one word, assign all spaceCount just after that word and there wouldn't be any extraSpace thing if there is just one word
            minSpaceForEachWord = spaceCount;
            extraSpace = 0;
            if (wordCount > 1) { // if word is more than 1, then calculate properly
                minSpaceForEachWord = spaceCount / spaceLocations;
                extraSpace = spaceCount - (spaceLocations * minSpaceForEachWord);
            }

			// Create current Line
            while (startWordIndex < endWordIndex) {
                currentLine.append(words[startWordIndex]);
                // Now add space but do not add space for last word
                if (startWordIndex != endWordIndex - 1)
                    currentLine.append(string(minSpaceForEachWord + int(extraSpace > 0), ' '));
                else if (wordCount == 1) // if word length is 1, above condition will fail always, so in that case put all the spaces behind
                    currentLine.append(string(spaceCount, ' '));
                startWordIndex++;
                extraSpace--; // even go to negative, we really don't care
            }
            ans.push_back(currentLine);
            currentLine.clear();
            charsTillNow = 0;
        }

		// Above while loop breaks leaving us handle the last line separately
        // we'll come here for last line. It has different rule
        wordCount = endWordIndex - startWordIndex;
        spaceLocations = wordCount - 1;
        spaceCount = maxWidth - (charsTillNow - spaceLocations);
        while (startWordIndex < endWordIndex) {
            currentLine.append(words[startWordIndex]);
            // For last line, just add one space
            if (startWordIndex != endWordIndex - 1)
                currentLine.append(" ");
            startWordIndex++;
        }
		// append the remaining spaces [totalspace - how much we already filled (spaceLocations)]
        currentLine.append(string(spaceCount-spaceLocations, ' '));
        ans.push_back(currentLine);

        return ans;

    }
```


PS: Above code can be modularized but I didn't want to break the flow of going through the code.
I have also one solution that's a little modularized that uses similar logic.
[https://leetcode.com/submissions/detail/714605666/]

