# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Real Math is done in this post. Think of this problem as a problem of expressing numbers without 0 in this number system. Simply perform the conversion using a base-26 system and manipulate the resulting string. Some related questions:

[171. Excel Sheet Column Number](https://leetcode.com/problems/excel-sheet-column-number/description/)
[2194. Cells in a Range on an Excel Sheet](https://leetcode.com/problems/cells-in-a-range-on-an-excel-sheet/)
[13. Roman to Integer](https://leetcode.com/problems/roman-to-integer/solutions/3692505/python-c-using-hash-table-w-explanation/)
[12. Integer to Roman](https://leetcode.com/problems/integer-to-roman/)
[273. Integer to English Words](https://leetcode.com/problems/integer-to-english-words/)

How to express n as a 26-radix number? Consider the following
$$
n=\sum_i a_i26^i
$$
where $0\leq a_i<26$. This can be done by successive divisions by 26. But there is no 0 in excel, so it needs a modification, i.e.
$$
n=\sum_i (a_i+1)26^i
$$
The process is shown in following pseudo code:
```
while (n > 0) {
    n--;
    q, r = div(n, 26);
    ans=(r+'A')+ans;
    n = q;
}
```
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The push_back takes O(1) running time for C++ string for appending a character. Then use reverse function to get the correct answer.

I don't use something like push_front (C++ string doesn't have it, can use insert or operator+) because it takes properly O(len(string)) of of elapsed time.

2nd solution does not use reverse function. Use  the formula (borrowed from number system with 0)
```
int len=floor(log(n)/log(26))+1;
```
to estimate the the length for string. There could be some better formula.  Before returning answer, check whether ans has whitespace, especially when 'Z' is obtained at the last division. 

3rd solution uses deque, O(1) push_front is therefore possible!!! 

The following theorem can be proved by using geometric sequence:
$$
a+a^2+\cdots+a^d=a\frac{a^d-1}{a-1}
$$
 # Theorem for length of the desired string
If n>26 then  len(ans)=d $\iff$
$
26(\frac{26^{d-1}-1}{25})<n\leq 26(\frac{26^{d}-1}{25})=(ZZ\cdots Z)
$
where $(ZZ\cdots Z)$ denotes the number consisting of d 'Z's. After some standard manipulations for inequalities, the exact string length formula is obtained as follows
```
int len=(n<=26)?1:ceil(log(n*25.0/26+1)/log(26));
```
No need for adjustment. Cheers!!!! With this correct formula, C solution is also done.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$O(\log n)$
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
 $$O(1)$$
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    string convertToTitle(int columnNumber) {
        int n = columnNumber;
        string ans;
        while (n > 0) {
            n--;
            auto [q, r] = div(n, 26);
            ans.push_back(char('A'+r));
            n = q;
        }
        reverse(ans.begin(), ans.end()); // Reverse the ans string
        return ans; // Return the reversed ans string
    }
};
```
